Between-speaker and within-speaker variations in British English¶

Lucas Mahler

Introduction¶

With English being spoken by a vast amount of people, it is natural that a large numbers of different communities evolved their own dialect. The major English varieties, such as British English, American English, Canadian English, Australian English and New Zealand English started to develop individually from one another at some point in history [1] . And according to Kortmann et al. [2], all English varieties differ in phonology, morphology, syntax and vocabulary among others.

This Jupyter Notebook tries to investigate the "Open-source Multi-speaker Corpora of the English Accents in the British Isles". Furthermore, in this Notebook we want to determine the articulation rate for each recording in the dataset and perform statistical analysis on it. The curated recordings contain audio clips of native speakers reading a line from a selected corpus of scripts. And thus the recording rate can be equated to the reading rate of the subject.

[1]: Smith, J. (1998). An Historical Study of English: Function,form and change

[2]: Kortmann, B., Upton, C., Schneider, E. W., Burridge, K., and Mesthrie, R. (2008). Varieties of English,

Dataset¶

The "Open-source Multi-speaker Corpora of the English Accents in the British Isles"[1] provides recordings with high phoneme coverage and phonetic environments that will be informative for all English varieties. Recordings were gathered from volunteers that self-identify as speaking one of the following British varieties, from here on called dialect: Southern English, Midlands English, Northern English, Welsh English, Scottish English and Irish English. The scripts used for recording contain Global Enlish accent elicitation lines and lines that are local for each dialect and its associated region on the British Isles.

It is crucial that the phonemic coverage is well balanced and that the scripts used for recording cover multiple domains to facilitate a number of different use cases and also pose no difficulties in natural articulation for the recorded subjects. The phoneme distribution of the recording scripts was designed to reflect a contemporary region-neutral British English accent. Phoneme frequency was kept to a minimum of 300 occurences each. The lines of the recording script were sourced from different sources, including public domain texts, novels as well as virtual assistant dialogues.

Since every person has their own ways of using language, i.e. their idiolect, 50 lines from the recording script were chosen to reflect individual use of grammar, choice of vocabulary, pronunciation, and intonation. Another 1524 lines were selected to represent phonological aspects of a wide range of Global English accents, providing enough phoneme coverage for a minimum phoneme frequency of at least 300 in total. The overlap of both idiolect elicitation and Global English accent lines are intended to be included in all English acecnts scripts. Furthermore, each accent region has their associated localized line that reflect common localities and names.

In total, the dataset consists of 17,877 recordings from 120 volunteers of which 49 were female and 71 male. The cumulative recording scripts contain 244,558 tokens out of which 7,646 tokens are unique. The total duration of recorded audio is over 31h. Utterance durations range between 9 and 169 characters with the majority being between 39 and 119 characters. Average duration for the utterances is 6.3s, the longest utterance is 20.1s and the shortest 1.62s. It is important to note that not each line from the script is available for all sexes, speakers and dialects.

For this investigation we only want to focus on dialects where both sexes are represented, namely Northern English, Scottish English, Southern English, and Welsh English. This subset of the original data then contains a total of 16.731 recordings. The following table gives an overview of the dialects used in the subset and the associated number of recordings.

[1] Demirsahin, I., Kjartansson, O., Gutkin, A., & Rivera, C. (2020). Open-source Multi-speaker Corpora of the English Accents in the British Isles.

# lets plot the waveform of the clip
def plot_wav(filename):
    spf = wave.open(filename)
    signal = spf.readframes(-1)
    signal = np.fromstring(signal, "int16")

    if spf.getnchannels() == 2:
        print("only mono files allowed")

    plt.figure(1)
    plt.title(s1['Transcription'].iloc[0])
    plt.plot(signal)
    plt.show()

In [9]:
import time
import contextlib

def load_file_get_duration_librosa(fn):
    clip, sr = librosa.load(fn)
    d = librosa.get_duration(clip)
    return clip, sr, d


def load_file_get_duration_wave(fn):
    with contextlib.closing(wave.open(fn,'r')) as f:
        frames = f.getnframes()
        rate = f.getframerate()
        duration = frames / float(rate)
    return duration



start_l = time.time()
clip, sr, d = load_file_get_duration_librosa(WAV + s1["Filename"].iloc[0] + ".wav")
end_l = time.time()
print(f"Loading with librosa took {end_l - start_l}s, clip duration: {d}")

start_w = time.time()
d = load_file_get_duration_wave(WAV + s1["Filename"].iloc[0] + ".wav")
end_w = time.time()
print(f"Loading with Wave took {end_w - start_w}s, clip duration: {d}")

Loading with wave is 1000x faster! Thus we will only use librosa when absolutely necessary.

        # Determine the dialect from the filename

    stat_df.to_csv("stat_index.csv", index=False)

Audio Preprocessing¶

Since we do not have the speech onset timestamps we need to trim the audio clips to not include silence at the beginning and end of each clip in order to determine the articulation rate. Manually trimming 16,731 recordings would go out of scope, hence automatic trimming is required. Librosa offers a trim function which does exactly that. Via experimentation, the cut-off value of 20db has proven to be a good trade-off between

To visualize this, we can utilize a mel-frequency spectrogram which is a representation of the short-term power spectrum of the recording, based on a linear cosine transform of a log power spectrum on a nonlinear mel scale of frequency (1):

In [170]:
def plot_mel_spec(clip, sr, title='Mel-frequency spectrogram'):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()

    S = librosa.feature.melspectrogram(y=clip,
                                       sr=sr,
                                       n_mels=128,
                                       fmax=20000)

    S_dB = librosa.power_to_db(S, ref=np.max)

    img = librosa.display.specshow(S_dB,
                                   x_axis='time',
                                   y_axis='mel',
                                   sr=sr,
                                   fmax=10000,
                                   ax=ax)

    fig.colorbar(img, ax=ax, format='%+2.0f dB')
    ax.set(title=title)

plot_mel_spec(clip_t, sr, title='Mel-frequency spectrogram of trimmed clip')

But in order to calculate the articulation rate of a given clip we also need the number of syllables of that clip and the clip duration as the articulation rate is defined as follows: $$\text{Articulation Rate} = \frac{\text{# of Syllables}}{\text{Utterance Duration}}$$

In [30]:
# calculate syllables in a given word 
def syllable_count(word):
    word = word.lower()
    count = 0
    vowels = "aeiouy"
    if word[0] in vowels:
        count += 1
    for index in range(1, len(word)):
        if word[index] in vowels and word[index - 1] not in vowels:
            count += 1
    if word.endswith("e"):
        count -= 1
    if count == 0:
        count += 1
    return count

# calculate the articulation rate
def articulation_rate(clip, transcription):
    sylls = sum([syllable_count(word) for word in transcription.split(" ")])
    # articulation rate = # of syllables / sentence duration
    return sylls / librosa.get_duration(clip)

articulation_rate(clip_t, s1.Transcription.iloc[0].strip())

Now we want to trim every clip in the dataset and determine its trimmed duration and the resulting articulation rate. Unfortunately, we now have to use the slow librosa.load() function in order to use it with librosa.trim(), hence we write the trimmed .wav files to disk, such that we only have to perform this time-consuming task once.

In [31]:
if not os.path.isfile("trim_index.csv"):
    columns = ['LineID', 'Filename', 'Transcription', 'Sex', 'Dialect', 'Articulation Rate', 'Duration', 'Tokens', 'Characters']
    index = list(range(len(stat_df)))
    df = pd.DataFrame(index=index, columns=columns)

    for i, row in tqdm(stat_df.iterrows(), total=stat_df.shape[0]):
        
        # check if trimmed version exists on disk
        if os.path.isfile(WAV_TRIM + row.Filename + "_trim.wav"):
            # load trimmed version of clip
            clip_t, sr = librosa.load(WAV_TRIM + row.Filename + "_trim.wav")
        # if it doesnt exist, load the raw clip and trim it, then save the trimmed clip
        else:
            # load clip
            clip, sr = librosa.load(WAV+ row.Filename +'.wav')
            # trim clip
            clip_t, index = librosa.effects.trim(clip, top_db=20, frame_length=256, hop_length=64)
            #save the trimmed clip to speed up later processing
            sf.write(WAV_TRIM + row.Filename + "_trim.wav", clip_t, sr)

        # retrieve transcription
        trans = row.Transcription.strip()

        # calculate articulation rate
        ar = articulation_rate(clip_t, trans)

        # for the sake of completeness, also save all relevant values from old dataframe to new dataframe
        df.LineID[i] = row.LineID
        df.Filename[i] = row.Filename
        df.Transcription[i] = row.Transcription
        df.Duration[i] = librosa.get_duration(clip_t)
        df.Tokens[i] = row.Tokens
        df.Characters[i] = row.Characters
        
        # save articulation rate
        df["Articulation Rate"][i] = ar
        # classify whether male or female
        df.Sex[i] = row.Sex
        # Determine the dialect from the filename
        df.Dialect[i] = row.Dialect
    df.to_csv("trim_index.csv", index=False)
else:
    df = pd.read_csv("trim_index.csv")

ANOVA¶

To asses whether the articulation rate differs significantly between the groups, we perform an analysis of variance (ANOVA).

In [41]:
no_ar = np.random.choice(no_df["Articulation Rate"].values, 2543, replace=False)
we_ar = np.random.choice(we_df["Articulation Rate"].values, 2543, replace=False)
so_ar = np.random.choice(so_df["Articulation Rate"].values, 2543, replace=False)
sc_ar = np.random.choice(sc_df["Articulation Rate"].values, 2543, replace=False)
In [42]:
import scipy.stats as stats

stats.f_oneway(no_ar, we_ar, so_ar, sc_ar)
Out[42]:
F_onewayResult(statistic=466.5039844545813, pvalue=5.257748994679656e-284)

We can see that there are significant differences [F=466.50, p<0.001] between the dialect groups when compared by articulation rate. Welsh English speakers produce significantly fewer syllables per second than any speaker of the other three dialect groups. In contrast, Northern English speakers produce significantly more syllables per second than the other three groups.

To evalute the effect of gender, we perform an anaylsis of variance on each group.

Concluding we can say that we can observe a significant difference in articulation rate between the different dialect groups. Northern English speakers read faster than Southern and Scottish English speakers while Welsh English speakers read the slowest. Differences as a function of sex were also observable as males generally produce more syllables per seconds than females across all dialect groups.

As most volunteers were employees of Google, similar reading capabilities can be assumed. However, as the number of recordings per dialect group greatly differ, it is to be expected that a more evenly spread out dataset would provide more insightful results. Additionally, not all script lines were present in all dialects, skewing the comparison a fair bit.

Classification¶

We now want to classify a dialect given the articulation rate, number of tokens, number of characters, and sex of a recorded utterance. A good first step is to use a support vector machine classifier:

In [151]:

As we can see, all of the machine learning models end up at a classification accuracy of slightly above 50%. The provided features, namely articulation rate, number of tokens, number of characters, and sex of a recorded utterance, apparently do not suffice for accurate classification of a given dialect.

However, as we do not have the same number of total recordings, not the same number of male and female recordings, and not the same lines for each dialect, this could be an influencing factor.

Conclusion¶

In this Jupyter Notebook we examined the "Open-source Multi-speaker Corpora of the English Accents in the British Isles". The provided data are recorded audio clips where participants of six major dialect groups of the British Isles read selected lines from a curated script. Four out of six of these dialect groups were selected and analysed.

After gaining insight on the structure of the data, we determined metrics, i.e. recording duration, number of tokens, and number of characters for each of them. Next we automatically trimmed the recordings to exclude silence at the beginning and end of each clip in order to calculate the articulation rate. Articulation rate is a valuable metric to investigate speech tempo as it allows all speakers of a given dataset to produce the same sample.

Statistical analysis of the data has shown that the articulation rate significantly differs between the dialect groups. Within dialect groups, the articualtion rate is also significantly different between the sexes.

But as the dataset does not provide the same number of recordings for each dialect and gender results may be skewed. Furthermore, not every speaker spoke every line in the script and not every line is present in each dialect group and sex which may also influence analysis. Age of the speaker was also not recorded by the curators of the dataset which could provide helpful clues in the investigation. However, since the speakers were mostly employees of Google, individual differences due to varying education levels are to be neglected.

Finally, we employed machine learning methods to predict the dialect given articulation rate, sex, number of tokens, and number of characters of an utterance. But support vector classification and multi-layer perceptrons both only achieved an average accuracy of about 50% indicating that the chosen features may possibly not suffice for proper classification. Speaker age could be a possible missing feature in order to perform successful classification.

Additional Material¶

The code below implements a convolutional neural network that is trained on the melspectrogram of a trimmed recording to classify the dialect. But since the loading of the clips takes on average 0.2s, totaling in an load time of ~55h for all clips, training on my personal machine is not feasible.

However, the melspectrogram contains vastly more information than the four simple features that were used earlier and thus it is to be expected that the resulting classification will also yield much higher accuraces.

In [114]:
# train test split
x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(df["Filename"], df["Dialect"]) # passing a dataframe also yields the indices
In [115]:
label_dic = {"Northern English": 0,
             "Welsh English":    1, 
             "Scottish English": 2,
             "Southern English": 3}

# generator that returns a batch of melspectrograms and their associated labels
def data_gen(X, y, batch_size=5):
    
    for i in range(len(X) - batch_size):
        # read in wave files from filenames
        clips = [librosa.load(WAV_TRIM + fn + "_trim.wav") for fn in X[i:i+batch_size]]

        # generate melspectrograms
        ms = [librosa.feature.melspectrogram(y=c[0], sr=c[1]) for c in clips]

        # up/downscale melspectrograms
        ms_res = [cv2.resize(m, (256,256))[..., np.newaxis] for m in ms]

        # create labels from Dict
        labels = [label_dic[l] for l in y[i:i+batch_size]]
        
        # yield tuple of features and labels
        yield (np.array(ms_res), np.array(labels)[..., np.newaxis])
